>>TAYLOR: So I believe
we need to be informed,

00:28:36.580 --> 00:28:37.450 align:middle line:90%
and the only way--

00:28:37.450 --> 00:28:39.990 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Neither one of those
positions is being informed.

00:28:39.990 --> 00:28:41.200 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Neither of those are--

00:28:41.200 --> 00:28:42.825 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's what
we have to take--

00:28:42.825 --> 00:28:45.190 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: I need to go
seek out the knowledge.

00:28:45.190 --> 00:28:47.470 align:middle line:90%
What is a school voucher?

00:28:47.470 --> 00:28:49.720 align:middle line:90%
Where does the money come from?

00:28:49.720 --> 00:28:50.597 align:middle line:90%
Etc and so forth.

00:28:50.597 --> 00:28:52.680 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, do your
own research on the topic.

00:28:52.680 --> 00:28:53.350 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: I have to.

00:28:53.350 --> 00:28:54.950 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But let's
take this further.

00:28:54.950 --> 00:28:56.908 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: That means I'm
a responsible citizen.

00:28:56.908 --> 00:28:59.800 align:middle line:84%
See, if I don't take the role
as a responsible citizen,

00:28:59.800 --> 00:29:02.590 align:middle line:90%
I fulfill Bernays' philosophy.

00:29:02.590 --> 00:29:03.972 align:middle line:84%
Your fans all know
about Bernays.

00:29:03.972 --> 00:29:05.430 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: They all
know this stuff.

00:29:05.430 --> 00:29:07.420 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Nephew
of Sigmund Freud.

00:29:07.420 --> 00:29:08.610 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's why I
suggested "Century of Self."

00:29:08.610 --> 00:29:10.540 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Bernays said
we're not smart enough--

00:29:10.540 --> 00:29:11.200 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: To make
our own decisions.

00:29:11.200 --> 00:29:13.240 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: --to live
in a democracy.

00:29:13.240 --> 00:29:15.850 align:middle line:84%
We need to be
orchestrated in order

00:29:15.850 --> 00:29:17.890 align:middle line:90%
to have a cohesive society.

00:29:17.890 --> 00:29:19.090 align:middle line:90%
Is that true?

00:29:19.090 --> 00:29:21.610 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's only true
if I let it be true.

00:29:21.610 --> 00:29:23.660 align:middle line:90%
But it's absolutely true.

00:29:23.660 --> 00:29:25.930 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So let's go into
this example you used.

00:29:25.930 --> 00:29:27.580 align:middle line:90%
This is a good example, right?

00:29:27.580 --> 00:29:29.550 align:middle line:84%
So you're being lied to
by both media sources.

00:29:29.550 --> 00:29:30.350 align:middle line:90%
That's how it is.

00:29:30.350 --> 00:29:31.240 align:middle line:90%
That's how it works.

00:29:31.240 --> 00:29:33.110 align:middle line:90%
It's only to support your frame.

00:29:33.110 --> 00:29:35.251 align:middle line:84%
It's only to support
itself and its advertisers.

00:29:35.251 --> 00:29:37.750 align:middle line:84%
There's no other point to either
one of those media sources.

00:29:37.750 --> 00:29:38.708 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: That's right.

00:29:38.708 --> 00:29:41.980 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So you're in a
consumer machine of advertising

00:29:41.980 --> 00:29:44.170 align:middle line:84%
and positions that
are going to position

00:29:44.170 --> 00:29:46.484 align:middle line:84%
that advertiser in front
of that conservative viewer

00:29:46.484 --> 00:29:48.400 align:middle line:84%
and this one in front
of this network in front

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:50.140 align:middle line:90%
of that, liberal buyer.

00:29:50.140 --> 00:29:51.880 align:middle line:84%
These are just
buyer-consumer issues.

00:29:51.880 --> 00:29:52.750 align:middle line:90%
It's not about news.

00:29:52.750 --> 00:29:53.950 align:middle line:90%
It's not about truth.

00:29:53.950 --> 00:29:56.920 align:middle line:84%
So you've been misinformed
on each of these.

00:29:56.920 --> 00:29:57.910 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:29:57.910 --> 00:30:00.205 align:middle line:84%
Now let's get into
more psychological,

00:30:00.205 --> 00:30:01.810 align:middle line:84%
because that's really
your background.

00:30:01.810 --> 00:30:04.190 align:middle line:84%
Let's just look at more of
the psychological components

00:30:04.190 --> 00:30:04.990 align:middle line:90%
of this.

00:30:04.990 --> 00:30:11.620 align:middle line:84%
What is it in us that once
we grab on to an idea,

00:30:11.620 --> 00:30:14.710 align:middle line:84%
insists on defending
it to the death,

00:30:14.710 --> 00:30:17.000 align:middle line:84%
whether we even believe
it's true or not?

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:19.120 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about more
psychological factors.

00:30:19.120 --> 00:30:20.280 align:middle line:90%
I think that's interesting.

00:30:20.280 --> 00:30:24.000 align:middle line:10%
>>TAYLOR: So there's what we
call compliance principles.

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:28.320 align:middle line:84%
One of those compliance
principles is consistency.

00:30:28.320 --> 00:30:31.210 align:middle line:84%
If I'm going to
be consistent, let

00:30:31.210 --> 00:30:35.500 align:middle line:84%
me give you a kind of
a study that was done.

00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:37.580 align:middle line:84%
If I come to your
home with a placard

00:30:37.580 --> 00:30:41.410 align:middle line:84%
to go into your window
to support an issue--

00:30:41.410 --> 00:30:45.760 align:middle line:84%
feed the poor--
and I convince you

00:30:45.760 --> 00:30:48.490 align:middle line:84%
that you would make a great
contribution to just put

00:30:48.490 --> 00:30:52.540 align:middle line:84%
this placard in your window,
front window of your home,

00:30:52.540 --> 00:30:57.610 align:middle line:84%
to support this idea, you
are 10 times more likely

00:30:57.610 --> 00:31:01.500 align:middle line:84%
to let me put a
billboard on your yard

00:31:01.500 --> 00:31:04.497 align:middle line:84%
than you would be if you didn't
put the placard in your window.

00:31:04.497 --> 00:31:05.330 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Of course.

00:31:05.330 --> 00:31:06.996 align:middle line:84%
There's already a
history of compliance.

00:31:06.996 --> 00:31:09.450 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: The reason is
you need to be consistent.

00:31:09.450 --> 00:31:13.260 align:middle line:84%
If I vote a certain
way, I need to defend

00:31:13.260 --> 00:31:18.300 align:middle line:84%
how I voted, because otherwise,
I'm admitting that I was wrong.

00:31:18.300 --> 00:31:22.860 align:middle line:84%
We have a need not just to
be right, to be consistent.

00:31:22.860 --> 00:31:25.680 align:middle line:84%
The compliance principles
exist of a number of them--

00:31:25.680 --> 00:31:27.340 align:middle line:90%
reciprocity.

00:31:27.340 --> 00:31:32.040 align:middle line:84%
Reciprocity is one merchants
use on us all the time.

00:31:32.040 --> 00:31:33.510 align:middle line:90%
We get something free.

00:31:33.510 --> 00:31:35.860 align:middle line:90%
We feel a sense of obligation.

00:31:35.860 --> 00:31:39.960 align:middle line:84%
So I am a charity,
and I send you a dime,

00:31:39.960 --> 00:31:44.820 align:middle line:84%
or I send you a gift,
all these return labels.

00:31:44.820 --> 00:31:49.610 align:middle line:84%
Because you accept the gift, you
feel more inclined to respond.

00:31:49.610 --> 00:31:51.690 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, it's a
manipulation, and yeah.

00:31:51.690 --> 00:31:52.740 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: That's right.

00:31:52.740 --> 00:31:56.610 align:middle line:84%
We are hardwired in some ways
that predisposes that way.

00:31:56.610 --> 00:32:00.270 align:middle line:84%
We know watching the brain
lifetime that if I sign

00:32:00.270 --> 00:32:03.690 align:middle line:84%
a check, just signing a check to
a charity I really care about--

00:32:03.690 --> 00:32:05.750 align:middle line:90%
my favorite's Women for Women--

00:32:05.750 --> 00:32:08.390 align:middle line:90%
I sign their check.

00:32:08.390 --> 00:32:11.810 align:middle line:84%
The reward centers
in my brain light up.

00:32:11.810 --> 00:32:15.440 align:middle line:84%
In other words,
I am being bathed

00:32:15.440 --> 00:32:18.440 align:middle line:84%
with those great
neurochemicals and the body's

00:32:18.440 --> 00:32:19.430 align:middle line:90%
natural opiates--

00:32:19.430 --> 00:32:21.500 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Because of
your intention, yeah.

00:32:21.500 --> 00:32:26.290 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: That's right,
because I'm hardwired to help,

00:32:26.290 --> 00:32:31.030 align:middle line:84%
to give, to be
involved, to care.

00:32:31.030 --> 00:32:37.120 align:middle line:84%
So psychologically speaking,
understanding that we

00:32:37.120 --> 00:32:40.230 align:middle line:90%
are built in a mechanical way--

00:32:40.230 --> 00:32:44.500 align:middle line:84%
and I am not one that believes
that the human condition is

00:32:44.500 --> 00:32:46.450 align:middle line:84%
simply a meat machine
that has evolved

00:32:46.450 --> 00:32:49.240 align:middle line:84%
through some Darwinian
process in the materialistic

00:32:49.240 --> 00:32:50.184 align:middle line:90%
reductionist sense.

00:32:50.184 --> 00:32:51.350 align:middle line:90%
I don't believe that at all.

00:32:51.350 --> 00:32:54.010 align:middle line:90%
That's all nonsense in my view.

00:32:54.010 --> 00:32:56.920 align:middle line:84%
But we're nevertheless--
we nevertheless

00:32:56.920 --> 00:32:59.470 align:middle line:84%
operate in very
mechanical ways, very

00:32:59.470 --> 00:33:02.590 align:middle line:90%
predictive mechanical ways.

00:33:02.590 --> 00:33:03.870 align:middle line:90%
You know all about media.

00:33:03.870 --> 00:33:06.100 align:middle line:84%
You spent a career
in media, so you

00:33:06.100 --> 00:33:10.780 align:middle line:84%
know that demographics
are key to advertisers.

00:33:10.780 --> 00:33:14.740 align:middle line:84%
But today we have
psychographics.

00:33:14.740 --> 00:33:19.540 align:middle line:84%
Psychographics takes the great
ocean, the five principle

00:33:19.540 --> 00:33:20.340 align:middle line:90%
primary--

00:33:20.340 --> 00:33:21.540 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Data mining.

00:33:21.540 --> 00:33:23.547 align:middle line:84%
It's possible by
data mining, Facebook

00:33:23.547 --> 00:33:25.130 align:middle line:84%
being one of the
primary contributors.

00:33:25.130 --> 00:33:27.040 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Well, if
you look recently

00:33:27.040 --> 00:33:30.550 align:middle line:84%
at Cambridge Analytics,
Cambridge Analytics

00:33:30.550 --> 00:33:35.890 align:middle line:84%
combined psychographic knowledge
with demographic knowledge,

00:33:35.890 --> 00:33:40.150 align:middle line:84%
allegedly, they claim,
to elect Donald Trump.

00:33:40.150 --> 00:33:41.170 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:33:41.170 --> 00:33:44.110 align:middle line:90%
What makes psychographics work?

00:33:44.110 --> 00:33:46.480 align:middle line:90%
Personality.

00:33:46.480 --> 00:33:48.310 align:middle line:90%
What forms our personality?

00:33:48.310 --> 00:33:50.470 align:middle line:84%
When I went to
college, I was taught

00:33:50.470 --> 00:33:52.600 align:middle line:90%
that personality is fixed.

00:33:52.600 --> 00:33:56.920 align:middle line:84%
It's like IQ or brain cells
that die at the age of 30

00:33:56.920 --> 00:33:58.930 align:middle line:90%
and don't regenerate themselves.

00:33:58.930 --> 00:34:01.960 align:middle line:84%
All of that's false to fact,
but that's nevertheless

00:34:01.960 --> 00:34:04.060 align:middle line:90%
what I was taught.

00:34:04.060 --> 00:34:07.210 align:middle line:84%
Today we would say changing
your personality is the best

00:34:07.210 --> 00:34:10.690 align:middle line:84%
way in the world for you
to make your next step

00:34:10.690 --> 00:34:13.000 align:middle line:90%
in self-improvement.

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:16.580 align:middle line:84%
But we're going to look
at your personality,

00:34:16.580 --> 00:34:21.219 align:middle line:84%
and we're going to look at
just how outgoing you are,

00:34:21.219 --> 00:34:27.659 align:middle line:84%
how agreeable you are,
your scale of neuroticism,

00:34:27.659 --> 00:34:31.219 align:middle line:90%
your extroversion, introversion.

00:34:31.219 --> 00:34:33.760 align:middle line:84%
We're going to look at these
primary characteristics

00:34:33.760 --> 00:34:36.580 align:middle line:84%
of human personality,
and then we're

00:34:36.580 --> 00:34:41.500 align:middle line:84%
going to say, well, if we
want to persuade this person,

00:34:41.500 --> 00:34:45.190 align:middle line:84%
they tend to be liberal,
but they're also Catholic,

00:34:45.190 --> 00:34:46.630 align:middle line:90%
religious.

00:34:46.630 --> 00:34:49.120 align:middle line:84%
We can approach this
person by talking

00:34:49.120 --> 00:34:52.280 align:middle line:90%
to them about right for life.

00:34:52.280 --> 00:34:55.159 align:middle line:84%
We can persuade them
to move our direction.

00:34:55.159 --> 00:34:58.430 align:middle line:84%
So what happens is billions
and billions of dollars

00:34:58.430 --> 00:35:04.040 align:middle line:84%
have been spent by governments
and private merchandisers

00:35:04.040 --> 00:35:06.560 align:middle line:90%
to understand our psychology.

00:35:06.560 --> 00:35:09.680 align:middle line:84%
We don't spend five
minutes to understand it,

00:35:09.680 --> 00:35:11.260 align:middle line:90%
but they have spent billions.

00:35:11.260 --> 00:35:14.750 align:middle line:84%
And now they gained the
ability to tweak us,

00:35:14.750 --> 00:35:21.350 align:middle line:84%
so we know that, look, there's a
group think problem that we all

00:35:21.350 --> 00:35:24.190 align:middle line:90%
need to be aware of.

00:35:24.190 --> 00:35:28.370 align:middle line:84%
If you get 20 people together,
19 of them are Confederates.

00:35:28.370 --> 00:35:32.300 align:middle line:84%
One of them is a subject, and
you begin to show them lines,

00:35:32.300 --> 00:35:34.580 align:middle line:84%
and you ask them, which
line is the longest?

00:35:34.580 --> 00:35:38.375 align:middle line:84%
This is a study that's been
replicated many, many times.

00:35:38.375 --> 00:35:41.660 align:middle line:90%


00:35:41.660 --> 00:35:46.190 align:middle line:84%
19 of them say the shorter
line is the longest.

00:35:46.190 --> 00:35:49.340 align:middle line:84%
The first one that's not the
Confederate, the subject,

00:35:49.340 --> 00:35:52.520 align:middle line:84%
initially may say, no,
that's the longer line.

00:35:52.520 --> 00:35:55.040 align:middle line:84%
But after two or
three passes, they

00:35:55.040 --> 00:35:58.460 align:middle line:84%
will deny what they
physically see in order

00:35:58.460 --> 00:36:00.090 align:middle line:90%
to go along with the group.

00:36:00.090 --> 00:36:01.890 align:middle line:84%
So we have this high
of consciousness,

00:36:01.890 --> 00:36:04.320 align:middle line:90%
this group think that goes on.

00:36:04.320 --> 00:36:10.010 align:middle line:84%
So what happens to many of us is
we get caught in a group think,

00:36:10.010 --> 00:36:13.160 align:middle line:84%
and we follow along
with that group think.

00:36:13.160 --> 00:36:16.550 align:middle line:84%
They understand this, those
people who would manipulate us,

00:36:16.550 --> 00:36:17.570 align:middle line:90%
that would move us.

00:36:17.570 --> 00:36:18.653 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Of course, yeah.

00:36:18.653 --> 00:36:21.380 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: So they can take
search engine results,

00:36:21.380 --> 00:36:25.040 align:middle line:84%
and they can shove something
artificially to the top,

00:36:25.040 --> 00:36:29.480 align:middle line:84%
and we'll follow suit, because
that's what everybody believes.

00:36:29.480 --> 00:36:30.890 align:middle line:90%
That's what everybody thinks.

00:36:30.890 --> 00:36:32.510 align:middle line:90%
That is the group think.

00:36:32.510 --> 00:36:34.210 align:middle line:90%
That's how we work.

00:36:34.210 --> 00:36:37.040 align:middle line:84%
Understanding--
"Gotcha" contains

00:36:37.040 --> 00:36:39.680 align:middle line:84%
all of these
psychological mechanisms.

00:36:39.680 --> 00:36:41.780 align:middle line:84%
It contains all of
the ways that we

00:36:41.780 --> 00:36:47.430 align:middle line:84%
have been massaged, including
some of the most horrific ways

00:36:47.430 --> 00:36:50.510 align:middle line:90%
that government has betrayed us.

00:36:50.510 --> 00:36:52.580 align:middle line:90%
We trust the media.

00:36:52.580 --> 00:36:53.780 align:middle line:90%
We used to.

00:36:53.780 --> 00:36:56.870 align:middle line:84%
Today people talk
about fake news,

00:36:56.870 --> 00:36:58.550 align:middle line:90%
but we used to trust the media.

00:36:58.550 --> 00:37:00.560 align:middle line:90%
I remember Edward R Murrow.

00:37:00.560 --> 00:37:02.630 align:middle line:84%
I would ingest
everything he said.

00:37:02.630 --> 00:37:03.980 align:middle line:90%
He had to be right.

00:37:03.980 --> 00:37:05.660 align:middle line:90%
He was a news reporter.

00:37:05.660 --> 00:37:08.730 align:middle line:84%
He only brought you
facts, didn't he?

00:37:08.730 --> 00:37:10.970 align:middle line:90%
But the world has changed.

00:37:10.970 --> 00:37:13.710 align:middle line:84%
It's all driven
now by consumption.

00:37:13.710 --> 00:37:16.470 align:middle line:84%
Remember the three principles
that we talked about earlier

00:37:16.470 --> 00:37:18.190 align:middle line:84%
and that were part
of the agenda?

00:37:18.190 --> 00:37:21.050 align:middle line:84%
Debt-- if we can
keep you consuming,

00:37:21.050 --> 00:37:22.970 align:middle line:84%
if we can keep
you on that path--

00:37:22.970 --> 00:37:25.640 align:middle line:84%
I once had a conversation
with an entrepreneur

00:37:25.640 --> 00:37:27.740 align:middle line:84%
who controlled the
Maxfield Oppenheimer

00:37:27.740 --> 00:37:29.900 align:middle line:90%
Trust out of Canada.

00:37:29.900 --> 00:37:32.956 align:middle line:84%
And we were talking about
this very thing, and I said,

00:37:32.956 --> 00:37:34.580 align:middle line:84%
I don't really get
the picture of debt.

00:37:34.580 --> 00:37:37.460 align:middle line:84%
Of course, if you're
in debt, there's

00:37:37.460 --> 00:37:39.060 align:middle line:90%
an enslavement idea to this.

00:37:39.060 --> 00:37:39.860 align:middle line:90%
I understand that.

00:37:39.860 --> 00:37:41.401 align:middle line:84%
But you have the
choice of that debt.

00:37:41.401 --> 00:37:43.400 align:middle line:84%
He says, let me
tell you something.

00:37:43.400 --> 00:37:46.610 align:middle line:84%
Eldon, if somebody comes
to your door, and they say,

00:37:46.610 --> 00:37:47.990 align:middle line:90%
I want your house, your ranch.

00:37:47.990 --> 00:37:48.870 align:middle line:90%
I like this spread.

00:37:48.870 --> 00:37:50.092 align:middle line:90%
This is just a nice spread.

00:37:50.092 --> 00:37:51.050 align:middle line:90%
I want you to move out.

00:37:51.050 --> 00:37:52.490 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to move in.

00:37:52.490 --> 00:37:55.294 align:middle line:84%
You're going to tell
them to go to Hades.

00:37:55.294 --> 00:37:57.085 align:middle line:84%
You're going to get
your gun, if necessary,

00:37:57.085 --> 00:37:59.850 align:middle line:84%
and drive them
off your property.

00:37:59.850 --> 00:38:03.480 align:middle line:84%
But Eldon, if they come to you
with a piece of paper in hand,

00:38:03.480 --> 00:38:05.170 align:middle line:84%
and they say to you,
you know, you just

00:38:05.170 --> 00:38:07.500 align:middle line:90%
didn't make your payments.

00:38:07.500 --> 00:38:09.930 align:middle line:84%
I regret to inform
you you're going

00:38:09.930 --> 00:38:11.970 align:middle line:90%
to have to leave your home.

00:38:11.970 --> 00:38:14.250 align:middle line:84%
You'll drop up
your head in shame,

00:38:14.250 --> 00:38:16.830 align:middle line:84%
because you've been
trained to do that.

00:38:16.830 --> 00:38:18.330 align:middle line:90%
You broke your word.

